title="Eric Zhao">Eric Zhao</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:blockquote>What is life if not but sorrow? 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  Wary now — I speak not merely 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  moment's gloom, despair all hollow. 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  Nay, only how we wear so dearly 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  keen the present's fleeting passage. 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  What happiness does linger through? 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  But dare I say — do not outrage! — 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  that better they had gone as due, 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  for far the road does whistful wend, 
  <html:br
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" />

  with sight ineffable at each bend.</fr:blockquote></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>